Backport of upstream Spring Boot fix for CVE-2026-40992
(GHSA-9wxp-w4px-32vh) to spring-boot-autoconfigure 3.5.3.

Enables SSL hostname verification by default in the Mail
auto-configuration.  When spring.mail.ssl.enabled=true (or an SSL
bundle is set), Spring Boot now emits
    mail.<protocol>.ssl.checkserveridentity=true
for JavaMail unless the new opt-out property
    spring.mail.ssl.verify-hostname=false
is explicitly set.  This addresses the improper certificate
validation weakness (CWE-295) documented in CVE-2026-40992.

Adaptations vs. upstream commit 327bef3a:
  * MailProperties.java target uses `private boolean enabled = false;`
    (explicit initializer) rather than the upstream pre-image
    `private boolean enabled;`.  Regenerated hunk against target
    context; behaviour is unchanged.
  * MailSenderPropertiesConfiguration.java target uses
    `if (ssl.getBundle() != null)` rather than the upstream pre-image
    `if (StringUtils.hasLength(ssl.getBundle()))`.  Regenerated hunk
    against target context; the newly-inserted block keeps the
    upstream `StringUtils.hasLength` idiom (StringUtils is already
    imported in target).
  * Test file hunk offsets shifted (target 3.5.3 lacks the
    `sslIsNotEnabledWhenBundleIsEmpty` test that exists in the fix's
    parent), so the surrounding test methods are unchanged but the
    line numbers are re-anchored.

